%S A396949 1,2,9,12,18,80,200,448,480,500,625,720,1080,1200,1215,1250,1568,1620,
%T A396949 1800,2025,2430,2688,2700,3000,3375,4032,4050,4500,5488,5625,6048,
%U A396949 6750,7500,9072,9375,9408,11250,11264,13608,14112,15309,17920,18750,19208,20412,21168,30618,31752,32928,35721,44800
%N A396949 Integers k such that omega(k) + Omega(k) = sopf(k), where omega is the number of distinct prime factors (A001221), Omega is the number of prime factors with multiplicity (A001222), and sopf is the sum of the distinct prime factors (A008472).
%C A396949 1 is a term (the empty product, for which omega = Omega = sopf = 0).
%C A396949 For k >= 2 write k = p_1^e_1 * ... * p_m^e_m with distinct primes p_1 < ... < p_m and exponents e_i >= 1 (so m = omega(k)). Then k is a term if and only if Sum_{i=1..m} e_i = Sum_{i=1..m} (p_i - 1); equivalently Omega(k) = sopf(k) - omega(k).
%C A396949 The sequence is infinite: for every prime p, p^(p-1) is a term, since omega = 1, Omega = p-1, sopf = p, and 1 + (p-1) = p.
%C A396949 If k has exactly two distinct prime factors p < q (i.e. m = 2), there are exactly p + q - 3 such terms with radical p*q; their exponents (e_1, e_2) satisfy e_1 + e_2 = p + q - 2.
%C A396949 Let pi(N) = #{terms <= N}. Empirically pi(N)/(log N)^3 ~= 0.04 for N up to 10^6, with the m = 3 stratum (three distinct prime factors) dominating in this range. Conjecture: pi(N) = Theta((log N)^3).
%H A396949 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A396949/b396949.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A396949 Integers k such that A001221(k) + A001222(k) = A008472(k).
%F A396949 Equivalently, writing k = Product p_i^e_i, k is a term iff Sum_i e_i = Sum_i (p_i - 1).
%e A396949 k = 1: omega(1) = 0, Omega(1) = 0, sopf(1) = 0; since 0 + 0 = 0, 1 is a term.
%e A396949 k = 2 = 2^1: omega(2) = 1, Omega(2) = 1, sopf(2) = 2; since 1 + 1 = 2, 2 is a term.
%e A396949 k = 9 = 3^2: omega(9) = 1, Omega(9) = 2, sopf(9) = 3; since 1 + 2 = 3, 9 is a term.
%e A396949 k = 12 = 2^2 * 3: omega(12) = 2, Omega(12) = 3, sopf(12) = 2 + 3 = 5; since 2 + 3 = 5, 12 is a term. Equivalently, sum of exponents = 2 + 1 = 3 = (2-1) + (3-1).
%t A396949 f[p_, e_] := p - e - 1; q[1] = True; q[k_] := Plus @@ f @@@ FactorInteger[k] == 0; Select[Range[45000], q] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Jun 12 2026 *)
%o A396949 (Python)
%o A396949 from sympy import factorint
%o A396949 def ok(k):
%o A396949     f = factorint(k)
%o A396949     return len(f) + sum(f.values()) == sum(f.keys())
%o A396949 print([k for k in range(1, 50001) if ok(k)])
%o A396949 (PARI) isok(k) = my(f=factor(k)); omega(f) + bigomega(f) == vecsum(f[, 1]~); \\ Michel Marcus, Jun 11 2026
